column descriptions¶

experiment_week : The column identifying the week during which the data was collected

channel_type : The channel through which the product is being sold, such as Warehouse Retailers, grocery stores, etc.

num_units_sold_in_week: Number of units of the particular product sold that week

sales_revenue_in_week: Revenue that the company made by the sale of the products

num_units_returned: The number of units returned by the retailer for the products sold that week. (Sometimes due to the retailers stocking the products for longer and returning products purchased from prior weeks this variable might be higher than the num_units_sold_in_week)

returned_units_revenue_loss: The amount of money that the company paid the retailer for returning the product

store_identifier: Anonymized identifier of the retailer

product_identifier: Product key from the database

category_of_route: Type of route used by the supplier to deliver the products

supplier_identifier: Anonymized identifier of the supplier distributing the product to the retailer. Most stores have a single supplier, sometimes a store might have two suppliers.

demand_projection: This is the target attribute, that you are supposed to generate. You should generate the demand for the number of units for a product by subtracting the number of units returned from the number of units sold

Data preprocessing¶

feature engineering required on:

  • internet retailers (highest mean revenue)
  • grocery (highest count, sampling bias)
  • store_384b1 (highest count, sampling bias)
  • supplier_identifier_77523 (highest mean revenue)
  • discount retailer (most losses)
  • bad routes (loss making)
  • binning stores, products, routes and sellers

from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
label_enc = LabelEncoder()
In [54]:
labels = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E']
list_of_feats_train = []
list_of_feats_test = []

for feature in ['store_identifier', 'product_identifier', 'category_of_route', 'supplier_identifier']:
    s1 = set(train[feature])
    s2 = set(test[feature])
    common = s1 & s2
    
    train_feat = train[feature].apply(lambda x: 'uncommon' if x not in common else x)
    test_feat = test[feature].apply(lambda x: 'uncommon' if x not in common else x)

    label_enc.fit(train_feat)
    train_labels = label_enc.transform(train_feat)
    test_labels = label_enc.transform(test_feat)
    
    list_of_feats_train.append(pd.cut(train_labels, bins=5, labels=labels))
    list_of_feats_test.append(pd.cut(test_labels, bins=5, labels=labels))

# creating new features
train['is_internet_retailer'] = [1 if x == 'Internet Retailers' else 0 for x in train['channel_type']]
train['is_discount_retailer'] = [1 if x == 'Discount Retailer' else 0 for x in train['channel_type']]
train['is_grocery_store'] = [1 if x == 'Grocery Stores' else 0 for x in train['channel_type']]
train['is_supplier_77523'] = [1 if x == 'supplier_identifier_77523' else 0 for x in train['supplier_identifier']]
train['is_store_384b1'] = [1 if x == 'store_384b1' else 0 for x in train['store_identifier']]
train['lossy_products'] = [1 if x in loss_prods else 0 for x in train['product_identifier']]
train['lossy_routes'] = [1 if x in bad_routes else 0 for x in train['category_of_route']]

train['is_internet_retailer'] = train['is_internet_retailer'].astype('category')
train['is_discount_retailer'] = train['is_discount_retailer'].astype('category')
train['is_grocery_store'] = train['is_grocery_store'].astype('category')
train['is_supplier_77523'] = train['is_supplier_77523'].astype('category')
